The paper deals with privacy-preserving social graph publication, which falls under the category of security and privacy (cs.CR). The paper specifically focuses on active re-identification attacks, which involve creating fake accounts to build structural patterns in social graphs, and leveraging tempo-structural patterns for strengthening the adversary. This suggests that the paper may also fall under the sub-categories of social and information networks (cs.SI) and cybercrime (cs.CYBER). The paper also involves experiments on real-life and synthetic dynamic social graphs, which suggests that it may fall under the sub-category of databases (cs.DB). Overall, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SI, cs.CR, and cs.SOC, followed by cs.DB and cs.CYBER.
